{
  "texts": [
    "Theories of 'low-information rationality' have put forward the role of 'information shortcuts' in making voting decisions (Popkin 1995; Goodin and Spiekermann 2018).",
    "Given that acquiring information about voting is costly, and that the impact of a single vote is derisory (Downs et al. 1957), voters have few incentives to get properly informed.",
    "Shortcuts constitute a cheap way to approximate wellinformed decisions, although their effectiveness remains insufficiently tested (Lau and Redlawsk 2006).",
    "Examples of information shortcuts include ideology, party identification, influence of opinion leaders, candidate characteristics, and of course, polling results (Lau and Redlawsk 2006).",
    "Shortcuts act as useful devices to simplify the collection and processing of data required for decision-making."
  ]
}